  <section class="moveRight" id="pi">
    <h2>Setting up the Raspberry Pi</h2>
    <p class="tutP">First You'll need to down load Raspberry Pi's OS, Raspbian. Then plug your micro SD card into your computer and format it. Once thats finished reformatting move the Raspbian disk image to the SD card.</p>
    <h2>Install Node.js on your Pi</h2>
    <p class="tutP">To install Node.js on your Pi run these commands in the Terminal:</p>
    <p class="tutP">wget http://node-arm.herokuapp.com/node_latest_armhf.deb</p>
    <p class="tutP">sudo dpkg -i node_latest_armhf.deb</p>
    <h2>Install PiGPIO on your Pi</h2>
    <p class="tutP">Next, you need to install the PiGPIO. To do this run this command in the Pi's Terminal:</p>
    <p class="tutP">sudo apt-get install pigpio</p>
    <h2>Install MongoDB on your Pi</h2>
    <p class="tutP">After that, you'll need to install the MongoDB. To do this run this command in the Pi's Terminal:</p>
    <p class="tutP">sudo apt-get install mongodb-server</p>
    <h2>Attach your components to your Pi</h2>
    <p class="tutP">Now you can connect your servos to your Pi. If you are using the same servos as me you will attach the brown wire to a ground pin, the red wire attaches to the 3.3v pin, and the yellow wire connects to the GPIO pin</p>
    <p class="tutP">The GPIO pins for the snare servo's are GPIO4 (Right Servo) and GPIO2 (Left Servo)</p>
    <p class="tutP">Next, attach your drum sticks to the servos (I cut my drum sticks in half to make them lighter) and you servos to the you mount</p>
